	<p>Izmalis, I say i don't know, because I don't know.<br />
<br />
I don't know what it is like for some foster children that live in abusive environments where they are raped, or beaten. I don't know what it is like to be a person that has very little possibility of becomming a contributing member of society. I don't know why foster children are many times more likely to have drug problems, to have learning problems, and to have run ins with the police. I don't know.<br />
<br />
But at least I am honest about not knowing, What you believe you know you call fact. There are no true facts here because the debate is not finished, and has been raging since the dawn of humanity. Your fervor in one direction, does not make me move in one way or the other izmalis, because I can truely see the merits of both sides of the case.<br />
<br />
I do believe however that the government should not ever have the right to force a citizen to have a potentially deadly procedure for what ever the cause against the citizens will. <br />
<br />
Because the other debate still rages, and this one is easy for me to put a finger on, I am clear on it. No one in the pro-life crowd ever deals with the ramifications of forcing people to do medical procedures that they do not want to do against their will.<br />
<br />
As I have pointed out before, are we going to start mandatory transplantation operations for siblings? or just people that are compatible? If new medical treatments become available with other potentially deadly, life altering consequences are we to say that those are mandatory too because someone else besides the person we care nothing for may die.<br />
<br />
I also don't hear anyone in the pro-life crowd saying what they really mean... sex is only for procreation, oh we could use semi effective means to attempt to avoid it, but none are fool proof, so sex is only a procreation effort. Sell that to society... you can only have sex when you want a baby.... and see how that goes over.<br />
<br />
BTW, they also never deal with the true ramifications of what would ACTUALLY happen if RvW is ever overturned. Countless young woment would endure the humiliation (as they did before abortions were legal) of coat hanger abortions, where not only operations were incredibly dangerous to the women, but they were usually performed LATER in the development cycle.<br />
<br />
To say you have total compassion for the embryo's is one thing, but to completely condemn the mothers, or women and men that do not want to be parents because of your personal beliefs is something entirely different and hypocritical.</p>
	
	
	
