	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Aeropig</b><br /><i>First of all I don't really have a clue with regards to the laws on abortion over the pond, but presumably there is a limit where the woman is considered "too far gone" for an abortion to be conducted. This is certainly the case over in the UK. The limit was decided based on the implications firstly to the mother, and was secondly based on popular medical opinion as to when the embryo can be considered a life form separate from its mother. The fact is there is no firm consensus on this and the debate regularly raises its head over here whether the limit is too soon or not soon enough. To chastise Shrewd for encouraging the abortion of a human life you are by default assuming that the embryo can actually be considered a human life. That is really what is at the core of the debate, assuming of course that personal and religious beliefs are left out of the judicial system of a multicultural society.<br />
<br />
Going back to the original post though. It seems to me that the court is refusing to allow this woman an abortion because it will cost the state somewhere in the region of $350-$400. One wonders how much it will cost the state and prison service in medical fees and continued care of the woman and her baby. I assume of course that she will not be expected to deliver it herself! If the state judiciary is going to reduce an issue as sensitive as this to simple monetary cost then surely the alternatives have to be considered. I wonder how much it will cost the education system and state administration for example to cater for the continued needs of the child. I would hazard a guess that it is probably a little more than the $350.<br />
<br />
Maybe the debate should be whether the state is protecting the purse of its electorate at all!</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Criminy, that's an even more horrendous position.<br />
<br />
It's cheaper to abort babies than it is educate and raise them, so let's abort babies to save the government some $$?  <br />
<br />
What an appalling argument.   I assume you are attempting to use what you perceive to be the state's primary concern or something, but maybe I'm misunderstanding.</p>
	
	
	
