<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Aeropig</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Oct 2005<br />
	Location: Coventry, UK
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I apologise for the way I have been misunderstood. I was clearly not making myself clear. <br />
The money issue I realise was never the real story. My last paragraph was meant ironically. I come from a country where all healthcare is free so making medical decisions based on financial frugality is alien to me. I did not mean for it to be taken seriously and I apologise if I have offended.<br />
<br />
With regards to the debate over whether abortion is allowed at all. Again I was being particularly obtuse and My point has been totally missed so maybe I can clarify.  I realise that the debate is based on the idea that some people believe that a child is a child from conception and some believe that is not the case and that it can not be considered a child until it can live independently. Most believe something that falls between the two extremes. Correct me if I am wrong, but my understanding is that the former extreme is a position taken by a number of religious organisations. Over in the UK it is mainly the Roman Catholic church that holds this campaign close to their hearts, I imagine that it is the same over there. My first paragraph was meant to question the propriety of allowing these religious beliefs, benevolent though they may be, to enter into a judicial system that is intended to behave justly to people of all beliefs. I don't believe that religion has a place in the decision making of any just judicial system. And I question the motivation of any Doctor that asserts that an embryo is a living "human being" from the moment of conception. Especially given the lottery that childbirth can be. This goes for politics as well. Once a law is established, surely there should be no interferance in the process. To be so desperate to achieve the desired result that they would pull out something so flimsy to justify themselves, their motive must have been either religious or political. Either is wrong in my opinion. That was the point I was trying to make.<br />
<br />
Again I am sorry if I have offended. It was not intended. I was merely trying to continue a very interesting debate on this forum. I have to thank Shrewd for posting these interesting and lively threads.</p>
	
	
	
	
