</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Thank you Srewd and Bufr for the education. In case you are interested I have included some information on the history of abortion within English law. The following is taken directly fro a BBC education website.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><br />
<br />
English Common Law agreed that abortion was a crime after 'quickening' - but the seriousness of that crime was different at different times in history.<br />
<br />
In 1803 English Statute Law made abortion after quickening a crime that earned the death penalty, but a less serious crime before that.<br />
<br />
In 1837 English law abolished the significance of quickening, and also abandoned the death penalty for abortion.<br />
<br />
In the 1920s English law added a get-out clause that stopped abortion being a crime if it was "done in good faith for the purpose only of preserving the life of the mother."<br />
<br />
This change officially recognised a little-stressed feature of anti-abortion laws; they were often intended to protect women from a dangerous medical procedure, and not to protect the life of the foetus.<br />
<br />
In 1938 the important case of R v Bourne decided in favour of an abortion performed on a 14 year old girl who had been raped - the court felt that the girl's mental health would have suffered had she given birth - and this established that the mother's mental suffering could be sufficient reason for an abortion.<br />
<br />
The judge (Mr. Justice Macnaghten) put it like this:<br />
<br />
"...if the doctor is of the opinion, on reasonable grounds and with adequate knowledge, that the probable consequence of the continuance of the pregnancy will be to make the woman a physical or mental wreck, the jury are entitled to take the view that the doctor ... is operating for the purpose of preserving the life of the mother."<br />
And the principle the judge set down in that case governed British thinking about abortion for nearly 30 years.<br />
<br />
The Abortion Act of 1967 revolutionised the situation in England by allowing doctors to perform an abortion where two other doctors agree:<br />
<br />
"that the continuance of the pregnancy would involve risk to the life of the pregnant woman, or of injury to the physical or mental health of the pregnant woman or any existing children of her family, greater than if the pregnancy were terminated,"<br />
<br />
OR<br />
<br />
"that there is a substantial risk that if the child were born it would suffer from such physical or mental abnormalities as to be seriously handicapped."<br />
<br />
<hr size="1" /></blockquote>There was some debate here recently due to the ambiguity of the statement "seriously handicapped". Some groups were complaining that certain limits on abortion relating to the age of the foetus were inadiquate due to the fact that certain tests for disability in the foetus were unavailable until these limits were nearly up. This meant that there was a great deal of debate as to what constituded a serious handicap and there was a call to tighten up these laws. <br />
<br />
On a more personal note. I have to say that my opinion probably falls among those of the pro-choice lobby. I know how difficult these decisions can be for women regardless of external factors/beliefs. In fact my wife was was unfortunate enough to have an abortion shortly before her and I met. She felt that she was forced into it and has found it very difficult over the years to forgive those that pressured her, as well as suffering greatly for what she sees as the loss of a child. I can imagine that the opposite can also be true if a woman is pressured into having a child when she is unwilliing and unready. This is why I think it is very important that the choice shouild be catagorically with the woman concerned and it saddens me to hear of another woman being forced into a course of action due in part to circumstance, but mainly due to another party forcing their contraversial views upon her.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
