	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Wouldnt it make more sense to try to make the message of the church more appealing to the masses...something that they would willingly follow (and by definition adopt the stance of the church on abortion) instead of trying to force their views on those that don't share them? Why is the church all of a sudden so anxious to interfere in the lives of people who willingly shut them out up until now?<br />
<br />
Im sure Iz will come out with a well constructed response on it, but aside from the topic of this thread, my note above serves the entire spectrum of things from abortion to gay rights, ID/creationism in the schools etc. It all comes down to what you believe in. Hell, science is just another belief system...even with all of the reproducible tests to prove theories, in the end its what you choose to believe in. So, its disagreement on what belief system should determine the laws of this country. When you are determining what laws will govern the people, do you choose the most restrictive or least restrictive? It would seem that some are all for reduced government interference but this argument really seems to take the debate to an entire new realm.<br />
<br />
I have read in several places that church attendance is at an all time high. Does this mean that people arent believing the message? The reason I ask is that there are enough polls out there supporting both sides of the issue that generalizing the american public as "Undecided" wouldnt be terribly inaccurate....<br />
<br />
Maybe this is the bigger problem facing the church that they dont want to address and instead are taking the "easier" route of trying to change the justice system.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
