Chutoi</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>See, this is what I would consider to be the articulation of a true "conservative" philosophy.  And one that I basically agree with, I suppose, except that I don't want anyone to chose to have an abortion.  <br />
<br />
I remember listening to my baby's heart beat at 11 weeks, and I certainly regarded it as life.  It was intensely precious to me then, and I would have mourned had it been lost even at that stage (highly possible statistically for anyone at that point).  I know I would have missed out on the best thing that ever happened to me - the concept that it could have ended there is unthinkable to me.  <br />
<br />
I recognize the inconsistency inherent in my own position.  So, I hate the abortion debate, and I think the rest of the country does too.  I don't believe all these women are murderers, which is what the pro-life basically calls them.  But I like to think if I were a woman, that would never be my choice.  I suppose the key is that I would be the one getting to chose, and not the government.  <br />
<br />
I do think Izmalis is likely right that scientific advances will increasingly challenge the concepts of Roe.  Certainly they will effect more of the public as people get ultrasounds, listen to heartbeats, and become more aquainted with their child in utero than previous generations.  You won't ever see me out there on the front-line advocating for choice - unless Roe is flipped and really stupid state legislation is introduced that imperils women.  <br />
<br />
Basically, it's an issue I don't want to be confronted with, and I would prefer to ignore it.  But it's hard to ignore...</p>
	
	
	
